The [Unified Socialist Party](/Unified_Socialist_Party_(France)) ([French](/French_language): *Parti Socialiste Unifié*, PSU), was a [socialist](/Socialist) [political party](/Political_party) that briefly graced, or perhaps haunted, the political landscape of [France](/France). It was formally established on April 3, 1960, a rather ambitious undertaking given the disparate elements it sought to unite. From its inception until 1967, the party was initially helmed by [Édouard Depreux](/%C3%89douard_Depreux), who seemingly had the unenviable task of bringing order to what could charitably be described as a collection of principled dissenters.

## History

The [Unified Socialist Party](/Unified_Socialist_Party_(France)) was not so much born as it was stitched together from the remnants and aspirations of various left-wing factions. Its formation was a direct consequence of the fusion of three distinct, yet ideologically convergent, groups. These included the [Autonomous Socialist Party](/Autonomous_Socialist_Party_(France)) (PSA), the [Socialist Left Union](/Socialist_Left_Union) (UGS), and a smaller, intellectually-driven collective associated with the journal *Tribune du Communisme*. This latter group represented a splinter faction from the established [French Communist Party](/French_Communist_Party) (PCF), having made their dramatic exit following the profound inner turmoil and ideological schism triggered by the [Soviet invasion of Hungary](/1956_Hungarian_Revolution) in 1956. One might say they had seen the writing on the wall, or rather, the tanks in the streets, and decided a change of scenery was in order.

Both the PSA and the UGS, for their part, were themselves splinter groups, having detached from the venerable [French Section of the Workers' International](/French_Section_of_the_Workers%27_International) (SFIO). Their departure was spurred by a deep disillusionment with the repressive policies enacted by the SFIO Prime Minister, [Guy Mollet](/Guy_Mollet), particularly his government's stance during the brutal [Algerian War of Independence](/Algerian_War_of_Independence). Adding insult to injury, these factions also vehemently opposed Mollet's support for General [Charles de Gaulle](/Charles_de_Gaulle)'s controversial return to power, which ultimately ushered in the [Fifth Republic](/French_Fifth_Republic) amidst intense military pressure and political instability. The three predecessor groups—PSA, UGS, and the *Tribune du Communisme* collective—had been developing increasingly close ties and a shared sense of grievance since 1958, making their eventual merger almost inevitable.

A [1981 presidential election](/1981_French_presidential_election) poster for PSU candidate [Huguette Bouchardeau](/Huguette_Bouchardeau), a testament to their enduring, if somewhat niche, political presence.

The newly minted party received a notable boost in 1961 with the arrival of several prominent political figures. Among them was [Pierre Mendès-France](/Pierre_Mend%C3%E8s-France), a former Prime Minister who had recently severed ties with the more centrist [Radical Party](/Radical_Party_(France)). He was joined by [Alain Savary](/Alain_Savary), another former SFIO member, who shared Mendès-France's profound opposition to [Charles de Gaulle](/Charles_de_Gaulle)'s ascendancy to power during the tumultuous [May 1958 crisis](/May_1958_crisis). Their entry lent a certain gravitas and intellectual heft to the nascent PSU, signaling its potential as a serious contender for the disillusioned left.

By 1965, the PSU, in a pragmatic if somewhat surprising move, aligned itself with the SFIO and the PCF. This unlikely alliance was forged to collectively support the candidacy of [François Mitterrand](/Fran%C3%A7ois_Mitterrand) in the [presidential election](/1965_French_presidential_election) of that year. However, this period of cooperation proved to be more of a temporary truce than a lasting alliance. In stark contrast to the more established socialist parties, the PSU notably and vocally endorsed the student uprising that convulsed [France](/France) in [May 1968](/May_1968_in_France). This decisive support for the student and worker protests further distinguished the PSU, solidifying its image as a radical, anti-establishment force. Following the seismic events of May 1968, the PSU progressively distanced itself from any further meaningful cooperation with the nascent [Socialist Party](/Socialist_Party_(France)) (PS), which emerged as the successor to the SFIO after 1969. Instead, the PSU embarked on a path to develop its own distinctive program, centered around the core principle of *autogestion*, or [workers' self-management](/Workers%27_self-management). This ideology advocated for democratic control of workplaces and economic structures by the workers themselves, a concept that, while perhaps idealistic, was certainly ambitious.

[Michel Rocard](/Michel_Rocard) stepped forward as the PSU's candidate for the [1969 presidential elections](/1969_French_presidential_election). Despite his intellectual prowess and charismatic appeal, he managed to secure only 3.61% of the vote in the first round. The party, ever the pragmatist when it suited them, once again campaigned for Mitterrand in the [1974 presidential elections](/1974_French_presidential_election). This particular decision, however, was met with significant resistance and opposition from the PSU's own dedicated supporters at the [grassroots](/Grassroots) level, who felt it contradicted the party's independent, radical spirit. Furthermore, the PSU pointedly refused to endorse or sign Mitterrand's "Common Programme of the [Left](/Left-wing)," which had been agreed upon with the Communists. This ideological divergence led to a significant internal rift. A sizeable section of the party's more prominent activists, led by the aforementioned [Michel Rocard](/Michel_Rocard) and [Robert Chapuis](/Robert_Chapuis), ultimately chose to depart from the PSU. They subsequently joined the newly invigorated [Socialist Party](/Socialist_Party_(France)) (PS), driven by the belief that they could more effectively function as a leftist tendency within the larger, more influential PS structure. Despite these internal struggles, the PSU continued to champion its core tenets, notably offering unwavering support to the workers involved in the [self-managed](/Workers%27_self-management) [Lip factory](/Lip_factory) conflict, a key symbol of worker autonomy and resistance.

In the [1981 presidential elections](/1981_French_presidential_election), the PSU introduced [Huguette Bouchardeau](/Huguette_Bouchardeau) as its candidate. She garnered 1.1% of the vote in the first round, a rather modest showing that underscored the party's dwindling electoral influence. By the [1988 presidential elections](/1988_French_presidential_election), the PSU opted to support the communist dissident candidate [Pierre Juquin](/Pierre_Juquin), who managed to secure 2.1% of the votes in the first round. The party's trajectory was clearly shifting. In 1989, a significant merger occurred: the PSU joined forces with the New Left for Socialism, Ecology and Self-management, which was essentially Juquin's political movement. This amalgamation resulted in the formation of the [Red and Green Alternatives](/Alternative_Rouge_et_Verte), a new entity that, in a testament to the ever-shifting sands of French left-wing politics, is nowadays integrated into the broader political group known as [Les Alternatifs](/Les_Alternatifs). The PSU's independent existence thus concluded, its various ideological currents flowing into new, albeit often familiar, channels.

## National Secretaries

A list of individuals who held the unenviable, or perhaps prestigious, position of National Secretary for the PSU:

*   1960–1967: [Édouard Depreux](/%C3%89douard_Depreux)
*   1967–1973: [Michel Rocard](/Michel_Rocard)
*   1973–1974: [Robert Chapuis](/Robert_Chapuis)
*   1974–1979: Michel Mousel
*   1979–1981: [Huguette Bouchardeau](/Huguette_Bouchardeau)
*   1981–1983: Jacques Salvator
*   1983–1984: Serge Depaquit
*   1984–1989: Jean-Claude Le Scornet

